# list secondary weights
 perl -wnle '/\[[\.\*][[:xdigit:]]{4}\.([[:xdigit:]]{4})/ && print $1 ; ' <allkeys.txt  | sort | uniq

# list tertiary weights
 perl -wnle '/\[[\.\*][[:xdigit:]]{4}\.[[:xdigit:]]{4}.([[:xdigit:]]{4})/ && print $1 ; ' <allkeys.txt  | sort | uniq

In allkeys-17.0.0
256 possible secondary weights (0x0000 and 0x0020 - 0x011E)
extra secondary collation weights 001F - 0127

29 possible tertiary weights

* do not store implicit weights from allkeys.txt, e.g. U+2F270


* check if reordering in discontiguous matching is correct

* possible to cast more of dump to C data structure so not always accessing
by byte offsets?

* put allkeys.txt version (and other metadata?) in output

* optimise sequence lookup or lookup for ASCII chars

* test more sequences other than l· (what are they??)

* Add gnulib vars in Makefile.am

* To avoid zero bytes, change 00 to 01 when creating binary dump.
(See TR#10 s.9.5.  This advice doesn't really make any sense as
it doesn't work for 16 bit values greater than FE00, i.e. what
can be represented in base 255 with two digits.)  But we could save
additional collation elements if the weights are too high.

* Read Implicit weights from allkeys.txt
 
* Unicode normalisation issues.  We should extend the data table
to include "canonically decomposable characters".  (See TR#10 s.9.5.)
(It's possible the table ("DUCET") already contains these.)
Or we should do the opposite and take these out of the table to
save space!
